input_str: A similar insight is precipitated by Quentin Skinner's Forensic Shakespeare, which like A Will to Believe had its origin in a series of lectures delivered in Oxford. As delivered, Skinner's lectures were marvellous examples of the lecturer's art — meticulously prepared, vivaciously and wittily delivered, enlightening and entertaining, and seasoned with a little well-directed malice.
